msgstr ""

#. type: CDATA
#: en/content/administration/stats.xml:288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shell> bin/otrs.Console.pl Maint::Stats::Generate --number 10004 "
"--target-directory /tmp\n"
"Generating statistic number 10004...\n"
"  Writing file "
"/tmp/List_of_the_most_time-consuming_tickets_Created_2015-09-08_14-51.csv.\n"
"Done.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/administration/stats.xml:285
msgid ""
"Statistics can be generated on the command line with the command "
"<filename>bin/otrs.Console.pl Maint::Stats::Generate</filename>.  As an "
"example, see the command line call in the following script.  <placeholder "
"type=\"programlisting\" id=\"0\"/> A report from the statistic configuration "
"\"Stat#10004\" is generated and saved as a CSV file in the "
"<filename>/tmp</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: CDATA
#: en/content/administration/stats.xml:301
#, no-wrap
msgid "shell> bin/otrs.Console.pl Maint::Stats::Generate --help\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/administration/stats.xml:299
msgid ""
"The generated report can also be sent as an e-mail. More information can be "
"called up with the command in the script below.  <placeholder "
"type=\"programlisting\" id=\"0\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/administration/stats.xml:307
msgid ""
"It usually does not make sense to generate reports manually via the command "
"line, as the statistics module has a convenient graphical user "
"interface. However, generating reports manually does make sense when "
"combined with a cron job.  Imagine the following scenario: On the first day "
"of every month, the heads of department want to receive a report for the "
"past month. By combining a cron job and command line call the reports can be "
"sent to them automatically by e-mail."
msgstr ""

